	faithHeading="Faith and the Bible in India"
	faithBodyHtml={`<p>India is one of the most religious societies on earth. Hindus make up about 79.8% of the population, Muslims 14.2%, and Christians roughly 2.3% &mdash; but in a nation of 1.4 billion, that small percentage is still around <strong>28 million Christians</strong>, more than the entire population of many countries.</p><p>The appetite for Scripture is enormous and growing. In 2024 India received about <strong>1.8 million printed Bibles</strong> &mdash; second in the world only to Brazil &mdash; and the Bible Society of India now produces audio Scripture in <strong>69 languages</strong>, from Hindi and Bengali to Punjabi, Marathi and beyond. Globally, digital Bible distribution has now overtaken print for the first time, and audio is surging: more than 1.3 billion audio-Bible listens were recorded in a single year.</p><p>India&rsquo;s linguistic reality shapes everything. The Constitution recognizes 22 official languages plus English, the census counts over 1,600 mother tongues, and Hindi alone has more than 500 million speakers. English is the bridge language of education and the internet here &mdash; which is exactly why a clear, free English Bible meets a real and present need, while translations like Hindi open the door to hundreds of millions more.</p>`}
